paper_summarizer (to user):

The relationship between the NF-kB pathway and inflammation in rheumatoid arthritis (RA) is critically influenced by specific microRNAs (miRNAs) that can modulate this pathway. For instance, the inhibition of CDK7 was shown to suppress inflammation in RA by blocking NF-kB activation, indicating a potential intersection of signaling pathways where miRNAs might play a role (CDK7 inhibition suppresses rheumatoid arthritis inflammation via blockage of NF‐κB activation and IL‐1β/IL‐6 secretion, Hong et al., Journal of Cellular and Molecular Medicine, 2017). Additionally, the study identifying lncRNA HIX003209 highlights its ability to aggravate inflammation by sponging miR-6089, linking NF-kB signaling with the competitive endogenous RNA activity of miRNAs (Long Non-coding RNA HIX003209 Promotes Inflammation by Sponging miR-6089 via TLR4/NF-κB Signaling Pathway in Rheumatoid Arthritis, Yan et al., Frontiers in Immunology, 2019). Furthermore, research demonstrates that elevated miR-145-5p activates the NF-kB pathway, thus exacerbating inflammation by increasing matrix metalloproteinase expression, suggesting that direct modulation of specific miRNAs may offer therapeutic potential in RA management (Elevated microRNA-145-5p increases matrix metalloproteinase-9 by activating the nuclear factor-κB pathway in rheumatoid arthritis, Wang et al., Molecular Medicine Reports, 2019). These findings point to a complex regulatory network involving miRNAs in the NF-kB pathway that could be further explored for innovative RA treatments.

