The NF-kB pathway is recognized as a crucial contributor to inflammation in rheumatoid arthritis (RA), and recent studies have illustrated how specific microRNAs (miRNAs) can downregulate this pathway. For instance, HAND2-AS1 has been found to interact with miR-143-3p, effectively inactivating the NF-kB pathway, which leads to suppressed activation and inflammation in RA fibroblast-like synoviocytes (RA-FLSs) (Mesenchymal stem cell-originated exosomal lncRNA HAND2-AS1 impairs rheumatoid arthritis fibroblast-like synoviocyte activation through miR-143-3p/TNFAIP3/NF-κB pathway). Similarly, miR-146a was shown to inhibit RA-FLS proliferation and inflammatory responses by targeting the TLR4/NF-kB signaling pathway, indicating that miRNA-mediated regulation has strong therapeutic potential (MicroRNA-146a suppresses rheumatoid arthritis fibroblast-like synoviocytes proliferation and inflammatory responses by inhibiting the TLR4/NF-kB signaling). These findings suggest that enhancing specific miRNAs could be a promising strategy for modulating the NF-kB signaling pathway in RA treatment. However, a knowledge gap remains concerning the comprehensive mechanisms through which other miRNAs may regulate this pathway, as the functional roles of various miRNAs need to be further elucidated for potential therapeutic applications (A20‐Binding Inhibitor of NF‐κB Activation 1 Is a Physiologic Inhibitor of NF‐κB: A Molecular Switch for Inflammation and Autoimmunity). Exploring the influence of additional miRNAs on the NF-kB pathway could yield novel insights and therapeutic targets for managing RA inflammation.
