paper_summarizer (to user):

The NF-kB pathway is implicated in the inflammatory processes associated with rheumatoid arthritis (RA), as demonstrated by various studies. For instance, the lncRNA linc00152 has been shown to activate the NF-kB pathway through the regulation of miR-103a, promoting inflammation in rheumatoid arthritis fibroblast-like synoviocytes (RAFLS) (Zhang et al., Immunity, Inflammation and Disease, 2021). Conversely, interventions such as the combined treatment of sinomenine and acupuncture were effective in downregulating the NF-kB pathway and subsequently reducing inflammatory cytokine levels in collagen-induced arthritis (Xu et al., Oncology Letters, 2018). Moreover, another study highlighted that the modulation of microRNAs, specifically miR-21, miR-100, and miR-125b, interacts with NF-kB pathway genes, indicating a potential role for targeting these miRNAs to alleviate inflammation in related conditions (Venugopal et al., Journal of Cellular Physiology, 2018). These findings suggest that enhancing the expression or function of specific miRNAs could represent a novel therapeutic strategy to downregulate NF-kB-mediated inflammation in RA, warranting further exploration of the miRNA-NF-kB cascade in the context of RA (An et al., Nano Letters, 2020). Notably, gaps exist in understanding the precise mechanisms by which other identified miRNAs can be effectively modulated to influence NF-kB activity and their overall impact on therapeutic outcomes in RA.

