The interaction between microRNAs (miRNAs) and IL-17 pathways in immune response regulation, particularly in autoimmune disorders, is underscored by the critical role of IL-17 in both protective immunity and pathological conditions. IL-17 is produced by various T cells and has been implicated in autoimmunity, as it drives inflammatory responses that, when dysregulated, contribute to immunopathology (IL-17 and IL-17-producing cells in protection versus pathology, K. Mills, Nature Reviews Immunology, 2022). In the context of inflammatory bowel diseases (IBD), higher levels of IL-23 and Th17 pathway molecules indicate a link between dysregulated cytokine signaling and disease progression, suggesting that targeting these pathways could be beneficial for therapeutic interventions (Lessons Learned From Trials Targeting Cytokine Pathways in Patients With Inflammatory Bowel Diseases, C. Abraham et al., Gastroenterology, 2017). Furthermore, research into Th17 cells indicates that they can induce cellular senescence, complicating the relationship between these immune responses and the development of autoimmunity (IL-17 and immunologically induced senescence regulate response to injury in osteoarthritis, H. J. Faust et al., Journal of Clinical Investigation, 2020). However, the specific role of miRNAs in modulating IL-17 signaling pathways remains unexplored in these studies, presenting a significant knowledge gap that could inspire new therapeutic hypotheses. Thus, investigating miRNA interactions with IL-17 pathways may unveil novel regulatory mechanisms important for managing autoimmune disorders.
