The abstracts provided do not explicitly address microRNAs (miRNAs) in relation to the modulation of IL-17 pathways within autoimmune disorders. However, some insights may suggest avenues for future research. For instance, the role of IL-17 has been highlighted as pivotal in various inflammatory diseases, including psoriasis and hidradenitis suppurativa (Fletcher et al., 2020, Clinical and Experimental Immunology). In particular, the IL-23/IL-17 axis is implicated in exacerbating chronic immune responses, emphasizing the need for therapeutic strategies targeting this pathway (Schinocca et al., 2021, Frontiers in Immunology). Lastly, emerging data point to the complex interplay of Th17 cells and their cytokine environment, which could be influenced by miRNAs, although specific mechanisms remain underexplored (Hundorfean et al., 2012, Inflammatory Bowel Diseases). Research focusing on how miRNAs regulate IL-17 signaling may reveal novel pathways for intervention in autoimmune disorders, leveraging the established importance of IL-17 in these diseases.

