paper_summarizer (to user):

The IL-17 pathway plays a significant role in several autoimmune disorders, particularly psoriasis and spondyloarthritis, whereby genetic variations in IL17A and IL17F genes may influence disease susceptibility and progression. The contribution of IL-17 cytokines to autoimmune pathogenesis is emphasized in various conditions, including psoriasis, where the TNF/IL-23/IL-17 axis is critical for maintaining inflammation (The TNF/IL‐23/IL‐17 axis—Head‐to‐head trials comparing different biologics in psoriasis treatment). Furthermore, studies indicate that targeting the IL-17 pathway through biologic therapies provides clinical benefits, although adverse effects are often reported (The Role of IL-17 and Th17 Lymphocytes in Autoimmune Diseases). The potential genetic influences on the IL-17 pathway, particularly regarding IL17A and IL17F variations, suggest opportunities for personalized medicine approaches in managing these conditions (The Role of the IL-23/IL-17 Pathway in the Pathogenesis of Spondyloarthritis). In addition, ongoing research highlights the importance of Th17 cells in stimulating inflammation in autoimmune diseases, pointing to a need for further investigation into how genetic factors might modify these pathways and responses to therapies targeting IL-17 (IL-17 in inflammatory skin diseases psoriasis and hidradenitis suppurativa). Overall, there is a consensus on the pathogenic role of IL-17, yet a gap exists in fully understanding the specific genetic influences of IL17A and IL17F on these pathways.

