paper_summarizer (to user):

Research indicates that IL-17 pathways are critical in the context of autoimmune disorders, where IL-17A and IL-17F genes play significant roles. IL-17 cytokines, especially those produced by T-helper cells, are involved in promoting inflammatory responses, which can lead to immunopathology if dysregulated (K. Mills, 2022, Nature Reviews Immunology). Furthermore, the transcription factor RORα has been shown to be essential for the pathogenicity of TH17 cells, suggesting that genetic variations affecting RORα may influence IL-17-mediated autoimmunity (Ran Wang et al., 2021, Nature Communications).

Contrarily, IL-17 may also exert protective effects, as evidenced by studies showing its anti-apoptotic role during the early phases of multiple sclerosis, indicating a dual function that is possibly influenced by genetic factors (Dominika Ksiazek-Winiarek et al., 2017, Journal of Molecular Neuroscience). This duality raises questions about the influence of genetic variations in IL17A and IL17F on the dichotomy of IL-17 function in autoimmunity versus protection. There remains a gap in understanding how specific genetic polymorphisms in these genes may modulate IL-17 responses and contribute to diverse clinical outcomes in autoimmune diseases, highlighting the need for further investigation (N. Charoenngam et al., 2023, Biomedicines).

