paper_summarizer (to user):

The role of interleukin-17 (IL-17) in autoimmune disorders is significantly evident, with IL-17 pathways often being activated in these conditions. For instance, one study indicates that the IL-17 pathway is a critical player in various inflammatory diseases, including psoriasis and hidradenitis suppurativa, suggesting that dysregulation of this pathway contributes to autoimmune pathology (IL‐17 in inflammatory skin diseases psoriasis and hidradenitis suppurativa, J. Fletcher et al., Clinical and Experimental Immunology, 2020). Elevated levels of IL-17 have been correlated with major depressive disorder, proposing that pro-inflammatory responses mediated by IL-17 may also intersect with mood disorders, which highlights an intriguing area for further exploration (Elevated IL-17 and TGF-β Serum Levels: A Positive Correlation between T-helper 17 Cell-Related Pro-Inflammatory Responses with Major Depressive Disorder, M. Davami et al., Basic and Clinical Neuroscience, 2016).

Apart from cytokine involvement, research has pointed to intracellular signaling pathways such as mTORC1 that regulate IL-17 expression, reinforcing the need to understand how these pathways could be influenced by epigenetic modifications, including histone acetylation (mTORC1 signaling and IL‐17 expression: Defining pathways and possible therapeutic targets, W. Ren et al., European Journal of Immunology, 2016). However, while these studies provide insights into the relationship between IL-17, autoimmune disorders, and regulatory pathways, there remains a knowledge gap regarding the specific impact of epigenetic modifications on IL-17 activation and its implications for therapeutic interventions in these diseases (IL-17 in the Pathogenesis of Disease: Good Intentions Gone Awry, Saikat Majumder et al., Annual Review of Immunology, 2021). Thus, the interaction between IL-17 pathways and epigenetic factors represents a promising avenue for generating new hypotheses in autoimmune research.

