paper_summarizer (to user):

Epigenetic modifications, particularly histone acetylation, play a crucial role in the regulation of inflammatory responses in rheumatoid arthritis (RA), significantly influencing the NF-κB signaling pathway. Histone acetylation profiles in fibroblast-like synoviocytes (FLSs) associated with RA are disrupted due to imbalances between histone acetyltransferases and deacetylases, suggesting a direct impact on the activation of inflammatory pathways (Epigenetics in rheumatoid arthritis; fibroblast‐like synoviocytes as an emerging paradigm in the pathogenesis of the disease). Additionally, TNF-α inhibitors have been shown to decrease histone acetylation at the RORγt gene promoter region, which is linked to reduced activation of the NF-κB pathway, thus modulating inflammatory responses (The immunomodulatory effects of TNF-α inhibitors on human Th17 cells via RORγt histone acetylation). Furthermore, a study highlighted that acute histone acetylation is essential in modulating gene transcription in response to inflammatory stimuli, impacting the overall expression of cytokines, which could include those downstream of NF-κB (Deletion of a Conserved cis-Element in the Ifng Locus Highlights the Role of Acute Histone Acetylation in Modulating Inducible Gene Transcription). These findings collectively suggest a pivotal link between epigenetic modifications, histone acetylation, and the activation of the NF-κB pathway in driving inflammation in RA, but they also underline a need for further exploration of the causal relationships and underlying mechanisms (Epigenetics in inflammatory rheumatic diseases).

