paper_summarizer (to user):

Recent studies highlight the significant role of epigenetic modifications, particularly histone acetylation, in regulating the NF-kB pathway, which is pertinent to inflammation in rheumatoid arthritis (RA). For instance, research indicates that Wutou decoction (WTD) treatment in collagen-induced arthritis rats leads to increased histone H3 acetylation and a decrease in DNA methylation, suggesting that modulation of these epigenetic changes could contribute to the anti-inflammatory potential in RA (Effects of Wutou Decoction on DNA Methylation and Histone Modifications in Rats with Collagen-Induced Arthritis, Liu et al., Evidence-Based Complementary and Alternative Medicine). Additionally, short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs) demonstrate an ability to inhibit histone deacetylases, thereby enhancing histone acetylation and influencing T cell metabolism, which plays a role in immune responses and inflammation associated with RA (Short‐chain fatty acids: Bacterial messengers modulating the immunometabolism of T cells, Luu & Visekruna, European Journal of Immunology). Furthermore, the study on Porphyromonas gingivalis lipopolysaccharide reveals that it significantly upregulates histone acetyltransferase p300 and NF-kB in stem cells, thereby suggesting a direct activation of inflammatory pathways through epigenetic modification (Porphyromonas gingivalis lipopolysaccharide stimulation in human periodontal ligament stem cells, Diomede et al., European Journal of Histochemistry). These findings underscore the intricate connections between epigenetic modifications, histone acetylation, and the activation of the NF-kB pathway in driving inflammatory responses in RA, opening avenues for potential therapeutic strategies targeting these epigenetic mechanisms.

