Epigenetic modifications, particularly those impacting histone acetylation, have been shown to interact with various compounds in developing novel therapeutic approaches across multiple diseases. For instance, in high-grade gliomas, alterations in histone acetylation driven by histone deacetylases (HDACs) present targets for pharmacological intervention, with HDAC inhibitors demonstrating therapeutic potential (Therapeutic Targeting of Histone Modifications in Adult and Pediatric High-Grade Glioma). Similarly, in periodontitis, the dysregulation of HDACs and histone acetylation correlates with inflammation and disease severity, suggesting HDAC inhibitors could modulate disease outcomes (Epigenetic regulation of inflammation in periodontitis: cellular mechanisms and therapeutic potential). Furthermore, flavonoids, known for their epigenetic properties, may regulate histone acetylation, promoting cancer prevention and treatment, thus opening avenues for dietary interventions in cancer therapy (Epigenetic activities of flavonoids in the prevention and treatment of cancer). However, gaps remain, particularly regarding comprehensive maps of epigenetic changes across different conditions, highlighting the need for integrated functional studies to enhance our understanding of the therapeutic potential of epigenetic modifications (Epigenetic regulation in major depression and other stress-related disorders: molecular mechanisms, clinical relevance and therapeutic potential). This ongoing research presents opportunities to explore new hypotheses on the interactions between epigenetic modifications and therapeutic compounds.
