There is a strong association between oxidative stress, cytokine signaling pathways, and rheumatologic conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis (RA), with the NF-κB pathway playing a crucial role in modulating inflammation. Rhoifolin has been shown to significantly reduce oxidative stress and downregulate pro-inflammatory cytokines (IL-1β, IL-6, and TNF-α) in a Freund’s adjuvant-induced model of RA, indicating that its therapeutic effects may be mediated through the attenuation of the NF-κB signaling pathway (Rhoifolin regulates oxidative stress and proinflammatory cytokine levels in Freund’s adjuvant-induced rheumatoid arthritis via inhibition of NF-κB). Similarly, pomegranate rind extract demonstrates the ability to decrease inflammation and improve joint function in RA models by downregulating NF-κB activity and pro-inflammatory cytokines (Pomegranate supplementation attenuates inflammation, joint dysfunction via inhibition of NF-κB signaling pathway in experimental models of rheumatoid arthritis). Additionally, auranofin also exhibits anti-inflammatory properties by reducing IL-6 expression via the NF-κB pathway, thereby highlighting a common mechanism where modulation of oxidative stress and NF-κB can influence cytokine levels and inflammation (Will Auranofin Become a Golden New Treatment Against COVID-19?). These findings suggest that targeting oxidative stress and the NF-κB pathway could provide a novel therapeutic strategy for managing rheumatoid arthritis and other rheumatologic conditions. However, the precise molecular interactions within the NF-κB pathway and the specific oxidative stress markers that may offer further therapeutic targets require additional investigation (Rhoifolin regulates oxidative stress and proinflammatory cytokine levels in Freund’s adjuvant-induced rheumatoid arthritis via inhibition of NF-κB).
