-----------------
Cytokine signaling pathways are crucial in the pathogenesis of rheumatologic conditions like rheumatoid arthritis (RA), and this relationship is significantly influenced by oxidative stress through the activation of the NF-kB pathway. For example, microRNA-146a (miR-146a) has been shown to inhibit the TLR4/NF-kB signaling pathway, leading to reduced proliferation and inflammatory responses in RA fibroblast-like synoviocytes, highlighting its protective role against oxidative stress-related inflammation (MicroRNA-146a suppresses rheumatoid arthritis fibroblast-like synoviocytes proliferation and inflammatory responses by inhibiting the TLR4/NF-kB signaling, Liu et al., OncoTarget, 2018). Wogonin appears to ameliorate RA symptoms through targeting the NF-kB/MAPK pathway, indicating a therapeutic potential in modulating oxidative stress markers and inflammatory cytokines associated with the disease (Wogonin ameliorate complete Freund's adjuvant induced rheumatoid arthritis via targeting NF-κB/MAPK signaling pathway, Huang et al., Biofactors, 2019). Similarly, rutin has demonstrated a protective effect in reducing inflammatory cytokines and oxidative stress by inhibiting NF-kB signaling, providing further evidence of the pathway's involvement in RA pathology (Rutin Attenuates Oxidative Stress and Proinflammatory Cytokine Level in Adjuvant Induced Rheumatoid Arthritis via Inhibition of NF-κB, Sun et al., Pharmacology, 2017). These findings suggest that modulating NF-kB activation could be a promising strategy for developing novel therapeutic approaches targeting cytokine-driven inflammation in RA. Despite these advances, further exploration of additional oxidative stress modulators and specific NF-kB inhibitors remains necessary to fully elucidate their combined effects on cytokine signaling pathways in rheumatologic conditions.
