The studies illustrate a complex relationship between cytokine signaling pathways and the expression of IL17A and IL17F in rheumatologic conditions. For example, the presence of IL-17F tumor levels in the tumor microenvironment of follicular lymphoma has been identified as a factor associated with poor survival (Assis-Mendonça et al., 2020, "An integrative microenvironment approach for follicular lymphoma"). Similarly, polymorphisms in IL17A have been linked to the increased risk and severity of rheumatic heart disease, emphasizing the IL-23/Th17 signaling pathway's role in inflammation and autoimmune responses (Poomarimuthu et al., 2018, "Association of IL17 and IL23R gene polymorphisms with rheumatic heart disease"). However, the findings regarding cytokine dysregulation in diseases like axial spondyloarthritis are conflicting; although some studies indicate no baseline dysregulation of key Th17 cytokines including IL17A and IL17F, others suggest significant variations depending on patient populations (Mease, 2019, "Ustekinumab Fails to Show Efficacy in a Phase III Axial Spondyloarthritis Program"). This discrepancy indicates a critical knowledge gap that may warrant further investigation into the role of genetic variants and environmental factors in modulating these cytokine pathways, particularly their influence on IL17A and IL17F expression in different rheumatologic contexts.
