Cytokine signaling pathways, particularly those involving TGF-β, IL-6, and IL-23, play crucial roles in the expression of IL17A and IL17F genes, which are integral to the pathogenesis of various rheumatologic conditions. For example, Mel-18 and Ezh2, which are influenced by TCR signaling, positively regulate the expression of IL17A and IL17F in Th17 cells, demonstrating the synergy of different cytokine signals (Reut Hod-Dvorai et al., European Journal of Immunology, 2011). Additionally, while IL-6 and IL-1β can drive IL-17 production independently of TGF-β, highlighting an alternative pathway for TH17 differentiation (K. Ghoreschi et al., Nature, 2010), the expression of IL17A and IL17F is significantly elevated in inflamed tissues from IBD patients, suggesting a direct link between inflammatory signals and these cytokines (S. Bogaert et al., BMC Immunology, 2010). Furthermore, the TLR9 agonist cobitolimod was shown to suppress IL17A and IL17F while inducing IL10-producing regulatory T cells and macrophages, pointing to potential therapeutic pathways targeting these cytokines in ulcerative colitis (Heike Schmitt et al., Journal of Crohn's & Colitis, 2019). The contrasting mechanisms through which various cytokines regulate IL-17 expression indicate potential gaps in understanding the nuances of cytokine interactions, which may guide future hypotheses regarding therapeutic interventions for autoimmune diseases (A. Huppler et al., Arthritis Research & Therapy, 2012).
