The role of transcription factors, particularly NF-κB, is pivotal in the immune cell differentiation and inflammation observed in rheumatoid arthritis (RA). NF-κB not only regulates the expression of pro-inflammatory cytokines but also influences the survival and proliferation of immune cells involved in RA pathogenesis (Leila Nejatbakhsh Samimi et al., "NF-κB signaling in rheumatoid arthritis with focus on fibroblast-like synoviocytes," Autoimmunity Highlights, 2020). Furthermore, nuclear receptor superfamily members, such as the NR4A receptors, interact with NF-κB to modulate immune responses dynamically, thereby impacting inflammation outcomes (E. Murphy and D. Crean, "Molecular Interactions between NR4A Orphan Nuclear Receptors and NF-κB Are Required for Appropriate Inflammatory Responses and Immune Cell Homeostasis," Biomolecules, 2015). Additionally, the non-canonical NF-κB pathway has been highlighted as having distinct roles across different cell types within the joint environment, suggesting a complex interplay that could be therapeutically targeted (A. Noort et al., "Non-canonical NF-κB signaling in rheumatoid arthritis: Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde?" Arthritis Research & Therapy, 2015). These findings underscore a potential area of research to further investigate how differential regulation of NF-κB-related transcription factors might lead to shifts between acute and chronic inflammatory states in RA, thereby contributing to disease progression.
