The NF-κB signaling pathway plays a critical role in the regulation of inflammation in rheumatoid arthritis, primarily mediated by transcription factors that influence immune cell differentiation. The dysregulation of NF-κB is associated with inappropriate inflammatory responses in conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis (Roberti et al., NF-κB Signaling and Inflammation—Drug Repurposing to Treat Inflammatory Disorders?). Various transcription factors, including those involved in IL-1β signaling, activate NF-κB, emphasizing the interconnectedness of immune responses and the inflammatory process (Nishimura et al., Role of Signal Transduction Pathways and Transcription Factors in Cartilage and Joint Diseases). The specific contribution of NF-κB p65, known for its role in transactivation, underscores its importance in chronic inflammation and potential as a therapeutic target (Giridharan & Srinivasan, Mechanisms of NF-κB p65 and strategies for therapeutic manipulation). 

