-----------------
The expression of matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) in synovial fibroblasts plays a crucial role in the degradation of cartilage extracellular matrix, particularly in conditions such as osteoarthritis (OA) and rheumatoid arthritis (RA). CX3CL1 has been shown to promote MMP-3 production in osteoarthritis synovial fibroblasts through specific signaling pathways, including c-Raf, MEK, ERK, and NF-κB, highlighting its contribution to cartilage destruction (CX3CL1 promotes MMP-3 production via the CX3CR1, c-Raf, MEK, ERK, and NF-κB signaling pathway in osteoarthritis synovial fibroblasts). Similarly, macrophage migration inhibitory factor (MIF) up-regulates MMP-1 and MMP-3 in RA synovial fibroblasts, suggesting MIF is another key player in the catabolic processes leading to cartilage degradation (Macrophage Migration Inhibitory Factor Up-regulates Expression of Matrix Metalloproteinases in Synovial Fibroblasts of Rheumatoid Arthritis). However, the regulation of MMP expression appears to be complex, as melatonin has been found to inhibit inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-α and IL-1β, which may indirectly reduce MMP-mediated cartilage degradation (Melatonin attenuates TNF-α and IL‐1β expression in synovial fibroblasts and diminishes cartilage degradation: Implications for the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis). These findings underscore a potential therapeutic avenue where targeting MMP expression directly or indirectly through inflammatory pathways may mitigate cartilage degradation in joint diseases. Further research could elucidate the specific signaling interactions and the therapeutic potential of modulating MMP expression in joint pathologies (Cartilage degradation and invasion by rheumatoid synovial fibroblasts is inhibited by gene transfer of a cell surface-targeted plasmin inhibitor).
