The expression of matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs), particularly MMP-1 and MMP-3, in synovial fibroblasts is significantly influenced by pro-inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-alpha and IL-1beta. For instance, in rheumatoid arthritis synovial fibroblasts, IL-1beta was found to enhance the expression of MMP-1 and MMP-3 in a dose-dependent manner (Noh et al., 2008, Rheumatology). Additionally, pro-inflammatory cytokines including TNF-alpha were associated with increased levels of MMP-3 and correlated positively with disease activity indicators (Liu et al., 2015, Genetics and Molecular Research). Resistin further complicates this relationship by promoting the expression of both IL-1beta and TNF-alpha in osteoarthritis synovial fibroblasts, which could subsequently lead to increased MMP production (Chen et al., 2020, The FASEB Journal). 

However, while the role of these cytokines in upregulating MMP expression is well-established, the precise signaling pathways, particularly those involving miRNAs such as miR-149 in regulating these interactions, remain underexplored (Law et al., 2021, Aging). Overall, the consensus highlights the critical role of TNF-alpha and IL-1beta in the modulation of MMP expression, indicating that targeting these pathways could provide novel therapeutic avenues in inflammatory joint diseases.
