The relationship between osteoclast differentiation and increased bone resorption is well-supported by several studies. For instance, osteoclast differentiation factor (ODF) is shown to mediate signals essential for bone resorption, indicating its crucial role in this process (Osteoclast differentiation factor mediates an essential signal for bone resorption induced by 1 alpha,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3, prostaglandin E2, or parathyroid hormone in the microenvironment of bone - Tsukii et al., BBRC, 1998). Additionally, the research highlights how the activation of the receptor activator of nuclear factor Kappa B ligand (RANKL) pathway drives osteoclast formation and enhances bone resorption (Ferric ion could facilitate osteoclast differentiation and bone resorption through the production of reactive oxygen species - Jia et al., Journal of Orthopaedic Research, 2012). Conversely, factors such as osteoprotegerin (OPG) can inhibit both osteoclast differentiation and subsequent bone resorption, illustrating a nuanced regulatory mechanism within this biological relationship (Osteoprotegerin inhibit osteoclast differentiation and bone resorption by enhancing autophagy via AMPK/mTOR/p70S6K signaling pathway in vitro - Tong et al., Journal of Cellular Biochemistry, 2018). This suggests a potential avenue for further investigation into therapeutic approaches targeting osteoclast differentiation to modulate bone resorption. The contrasting roles of different signaling molecules within osteoclastogenesis represent a vital knowledge gap that could inform the development of new osteoporosis treatments.
