The structural support of bone tissue by extracellular matrix (ECM) components is emphasized by several studies. Fibronectin, a significant ECM protein, plays a crucial role in the interaction between mesenchymal cells and the collagen matrix during bone formation, suggesting its importance in stabilizing the bone structure (Synthesis and localization of fibronectin during collagenous matrix-mesenchymal cell interaction and differentiation of cartilage and bone in vivo, R. Weiss & A. Reddi, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 1980). Additionally, a broad range of ECM components regulates the behavior of mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs), affecting functions like adhesion and proliferation, highlighting the intricate role of the ECM in bone tissue dynamics (Toward biomimetic materials in bone regeneration: functional behavior of mesenchymal stem cells on a broad spectrum of extracellular matrix components, A. Ode et al., Journal of Biomedical Materials Research. Part A, 2010). Furthermore, bone marrow stromal cells are shown to produce extensive ECM proteins, which may enhance their functionality and contextual interactions with the bone ECM, further linking the structural components with cellular behavior (Global transcriptome analysis of human bone marrow stromal cells reveals proliferative, mobile and interactive cells that produce abundant extracellular matrix proteins, Jiaqiang Ren et al., Cytotherapy, 2011). This synthesis of findings indicates that while significant knowledge exists about specific roles of individual ECM components, further investigation is needed to determine their collective impact on bone regeneration and development.
